<img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-1704692 lazyload lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-598x598.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="1280" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-598x598.jpg 598w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-58x58.jpg 58w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-116x116.jpg 116w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-100x100.jpg 100w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-200x200.jpg 200w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-240x240.jpg 240w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-480x480.jpg 480w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1-600x600.jpg 600w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/twitter-1.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> They say you’re living on the edge, but you aren’t. Man has somehow lived through nature’s gifts of cliffs, mountains and edges. Here are 5 places where people literally live on the edge. Switzerland The Alpine town of Lauterbrunnen has distinct chalet-style houses plus small village churches. Asides the erected buildings the breathtaking serenity of nature.   With soaring rocks, cliffs and flowery fields.   Greece In the Greek island  is Fira, the capital of Santorini. It is a community popular for its white-washed houses erected on the edge of a 400-meter (1,312 feet) high caldera on the western edge of the semi-circular island of Thera. At the top of this delightful community, you can appreciate extraordinary views of a volcano, the intense blue of the sea below and one of the most popular nightfalls in the area. Italy Positano is a tiny beautiful town with wonderful seaside views, on the popular Amalfi Coast, in Campania, Italy. The city is extensive of whirling colourful buildings seated on an territory on the face of a cliff. <img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-1704708 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-1062x598.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="720" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-1062x598.jpg 1062w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-640x360.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-1536x864.jpg 1536w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-320x180.jpg 320w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-278x156.jpg 278w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-556x312.jpg 556w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-515x290.jpg 515w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-1030x580.jpg 1030w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-712x401.jpg 712w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-1424x802.jpg 1424w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1-600x338.jpg 600w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/book-1.jpg 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" />  Mexico Acapulco rose to fame by the 1950s as a breakout for stars and millionaires. However, it continues to be a popular traveller destination particularly among Mexicans. During spring breaks it’s also a favourite destination mostly with US college students. France Rocamadour, located in France in south-western has been a magnet attracting travellers because of its incredible assortment of cliff residences, ancient relics and sacred sanctuaries erected on a limestone cliff which is 1,500 feet above the Alzou River Gorge. A wondrous chapel and many oratories of this medieval village climb in levels up to the side of a cliff and come off like to oppose the statutes of gravity.  